 BANDWIDTH n. 1. Used by hackers in a generalization of its techniucal
meaning as the volume of information per unit time that a computer, person or
transmission medium can handle. "Those are amazing graphics but I missed some
of the detail --- not enough bandwidth, I guess." 2. Attention span. 3. Very
loosely, total data volume. "Never underestimate the bandwidth of a
station-wagon full of magtapes." 4. On USENET, a measure of network capacity
that is often wasted by people complaining about how network news items
posted by others are a waste of bandwidth.